snippet.textDisplay:
Phase change will always be more efficient than water -- it's far superior at moving heat. The typical liquid side of a home's AC system is 1/4" or 3/8" copper tube. The whole home is cooled and heated via that tiny tube. The loop phase change is superior to the traditional heat pipes found in your typical coolers. Not sure why they haven't utilized a loop solution in laptops yet.

Keep in mind, it requires MORE energy to turn 100c water into steam, than it does to warm 0c water to 100c. Phase change is king!

snippet.textDisplay:
There's nothing more annoying than when a YouTuber uses a clickbait title on a video that doesn't need it, then proceeds to act as if it's actually true. The fact is, Mini ITX sized desktop builds are going to be mainstream in the near future, and water cooling is hard to beat when you're talking about cramming as much power as possible into a tiny case. So unless they can make a low profile version that's more like 1/4 that size? Water cooling will never be dead.

Also, based on how this cooler is described, it's technically still a water cooler. It's just an all-in-one water cooler.
snippet.textOriginal:
There's nothing more annoying than when a YouTuber uses a clickbait title on a video that doesn't need it, then proceeds to act as if it's actually true. The fact is, Mini ITX sized desktop builds are going to be mainstream in the near future, and water cooling is hard to beat when you're talking about cramming as much power as possible into a tiny case. So unless they can make a low profile version that's more like 1/4 that size? Water cooling will never be dead. 

Also, based on how this cooler is described, it's technically still a water cooler. It's just an all-in-one water cooler.

snippet.textDisplay: It's amazing to see how we've use the basic physics of heat pipe technology over the years. A couple of years ago I read a fascinating book on the history of the SAS - the UK Special Air Service, the elite special forces group set up by Captain Stirling during the Second World War. The SAS had their origins in an outfit known as the "Long Range Desert Group", a division of the British Army stationed in Northern Africa. That force experimented with specially modified jeeps that were able to survive in the desert by using heat pipe technology. The engines were water cooled - and of course the water in the cooling system quickly boiled - but the steam was allowed to escape the engine coolant loop by an extra pipe set "up high" on the block, where liquid water could not flow. The escape pipe led out through the radiator grill to a toughened vessel - like a one-gallon metal tank - bolted to the front of the vehicle. Here, the steam was allowed to expand - and basic thermal dynamics let it cool, condense and cool water. The water ran down the sides of the can to a return pipe that ran it back in to the engine cooling system. Pretty much the exact same principle that Linus described in this video. Yes, wwayyy off topic. I'll see myself out.
